<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 92 / UK Company News: Guide for banks on securitisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BANK of England has published guidelines for the securitisation of
credit card receivables by banks. This process allows banks to bundle up a
large number of credit card receivables and sell them, via the bond markets,
to outside investors - a practice common in the US, writes Philip Coggan.
Through securitisation, banks will be able to remove credit card receivables
from their balance sheets - thereby freeing them to make other loans. A
number of banks, including Barclays, have been pressing for this change.
The Bank of England has been concerned to ensure that, before such loans can
be taken off balance sheet, all the risks involved in the loans are removed
from the banks. In particular, where goods bought via credit cards are
faulty, the customer may have a claim against the card issuer; it wants
banks to receive an indemnity against such liabilities, or take out
insurance to cover the risk.
In addition, the Bank intends to impose a limit on the amount of credit card
receivables which a bank can remove from its balance sheet. The limit, which
will be reviewed periodically, has been initially set at 10 per cent of a
bank's capital base.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
