<DOCNO>FT922-10010</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEEBIAAYFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920505
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 92 / Clinton attains his finest hour: Democratic frontrunner sets
out his vision for the presidency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW ORLEANS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WHETHER or not Governor Bill Clinton's campaign for the presidency strikes
gold, he may reflect when it is over on the high and low water marks on the
long road to the White House or back to Arkansas.
If so, he would surely conclude that one of his finest oratorical hours took
place in New Orleans at the weekend. On Saturday, less than 72 hours after
Los Angeles had erupted in flames, he delivered a speech which defined as
well as any why he wanted to be president and of what sort of country he
wished to preside over.
'Of course I want to be president,' he said. 'But, more important than that,
I want you to think of what kind of citizen you want to be.'
The 'you' in this case were members of the Democratic Leadership Council,
who are very much Mr Clinton's sort of people - professionals, committed,
successful. Rev Jesse Jackson once unkindly called the DLC the 'Democratic
leisure club' and, judging by the number of its members toting golf clubs
off the charter flight last week, it was impossible to deny he had a point.
But it was also impossible to deny that Mr Clinton spoke with real feeling.
He did so without the benefit of a prepared text or teleprompter, relying
on, but not referring to, his hand-scrawled notes. While, after so much
campaigning, no speech can be said to be wholly spontaneous, the performance
served to remind how good a public speaker Mr Clinton can be.
The traditions of southern oratory are not lost on him.
He set out his stall early. 'Thomas Jefferson once said that the crisis of
slavery is a fire bell in the night. The crisis in Los Angeles is now our
fire bell in the night.'
His alarm was over race, fear and social division.
It was one thing for the nation to unite in response to a crisis, be it the
Gulf war, the assassination of a public figure, or Magic Johnson, the
basketball player, contracting the HIV virus. 'But when the crisis passes,
when we go back to the day-to-day ordinary living of life, I say we are not
a community.
'We should be afraid, my fellow Americans. But we must face our fears and
stop running from them.' And this could only begin with the recognition of
'the hard truth' that race was at the root of much of this.
'White Americans all too often fear that violence has only a black face.
They see it on the news, they see it in their movies, they are gripped by
the isolation of their own experience. Blacks, too, often fear that too
often violence has a black face - and no one cares.'
What happened in Los Angeles was 'the plaintive cry of millions of Americans
who know there is no community today'.
But this was not the bleeding heart liberal Clinton, or the professional
governor with a million programmes for every problem, or the politician
seeking to assign partisan blame. Indeed, he blamed his own party as much as
the Republicans for having let the country down.
Of the Democrats, he said: 'Too often people think we haven't paid as much
attention to the victims of crime as we should have. Too often they think we
have clung to putting their tax money into programmes year after year,
whether they work or not. Too often we have heard members of our party say
that those who seek to reform the welfare system are the enemies of the
poor.
'Too often we have had a leadership in our nation's capital paralysed and
divided, mirroring a country all too divided. And when that happens, we all
pay.'
He conceded that, as a politician, his credibility was not high. 'People say
you are a politician, how can I believe you?' There was no answer unless
people were honest with themselves, honest about race and crime and honest
enough to say that 'here is what the leaders should do and here is what the
people must do'. Without that ingredient there could only be frustration.
With it, he had some ideas: better community policing, community service,
not incarceration for the youngest and least violent offenders, serious gun
control ('you cannot make the case that a kid's need for an assault weapon
is protected under the constitution of the United States'), strengthening
families, including forced extraction of delinquent child support payments,
and turning schools into meaningful experiences.
A lot of what he said derives from his personal experience; he was the child
of a broken home, but brought up inside a strong extended family. He sends
his daughter to a racially mixed state school in Little Rock and lived
through, as a student, the 1968 urban riots in Washington.
Perfection is, of course, unattainable and he clearly has not always
attained it. But that does not mean he is insincere or cannot legitimately
dream.
'What is killing us today is that millions of Americans get up every day and
do not believe tomorrow will be better and do not believe they can make a
difference.' In New Orleans he eloquently set out the case that neither is
necessarily so.
</TEXT>
