<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow pushed lower by sell
programmes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
A ROUND of sell programmes pushed US stocks lower yesterday, but trading was
quiet as traders headed home early amid fears that violence would spill on
to the streets of New York in the aftermath of the Los Angeles riots, writes
Karen Zagor in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average lost 23.03 to close at 3,336.09, with only
177.4m shares changing hands on the big board. Declining issues led
advancing by 908 to 775. Among other market indices, the broadly-based
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was off 2.43 at 412.52 while the Nasdaq composite slid
0.54 to 578.14. On Thursday, the Dow advanced 25.94 to 3,359.12.
There was some uneasiness following an unexpectedly weak purchasing
managers' index report for April, which fell to 51.3 per cent from 54.1 per
cent in March. The market had expected the April index to advance to about
55 per cent.
Shares in Chrysler continued to lose ground in the wake of the company's
unsatisfactory first quarter results. The stock closed at Dollars 18 1/2 ,
down Dollars  7/8 , after falling Dollars  3/8 a day earlier. Ford lost
Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 44 1/8 , after sliding Dollars  3/8 on Thursday and
General Motors eased Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 40 3/4 , on top of its previous
Dollars  7/8 decline.
In the pharmaceutical sector, Glaxo Holdings' American depositary receipts
fell Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 25 1/2 . The stock had advanced Dollars  7/8
on Thursday on news that the oral form of the company's migraine drug had
received UK regulatory approval. Among other drug company issues, Merck slid
Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 143 3/4 , American Home Products added Dollars 1 to
Dollars 78 1/4 and Pfizer lost Dollars  5/8 to Dollars 70 7/8 .
The sell-off in insurance issues continued, with General Re, the biggest US
reinsurance group, sliding Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 78 5/8 , Cigna losing
Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 51, Travelers off Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 20 3/8 and
Aetna down Dollars 1 to Dollars 41 5/8 . Only American International Group
bucked the trend, adding Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 83 1/2 . AIG's strong first
quarter profits were overshadowed by General Re's warning that its
underwriting results would probably be disappointing for the remainder of
the year.
Among entertainment stocks, Walt Disney firmed Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 146
after PaineWebber upgraded its rating. Paramount Communications slipped
Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 45 1/4 in thin trading.
In the secondary market, Western Capital Investment soared Dollars 3 5/8 to
Dollars 13 1/4 on news that the Colorado-based Savings &amp; Loan had agreed to
be acquired by First Bank System for Dollars 150m. On the big board, First
Bank fell Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 25 3/4 .
Trading was also active in Synergen, which climbed Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars
39 after the company posted a first quarter loss of 2 cents a share against
14 cents a year earlier.
Canada
TORONTO stocks ended mixed. The TSE-300 composite index added 1.5 to close
at 3357.06 in volume of 23.3m shares. Among active issues, Morgan Financial
Corp was flat at CDollars 0.055, Rogers class B gained CDollars  1/8 to
CDollars 13 5/8 , Encor eased CDollars 0.01 to CDollars 0.33 and Corona
firmed CDollars 0.20 to CDollars 4.45.
