<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 92 / Spens allowed to re-open fight for an acquittal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND HUGHES, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD SPENS, former corporate finance managing director at Henry Ansbacher,
the merchant bank, was yesterday given leave to challenge the refusal to
grant him a formal acquittal after the collapse of the second Guinness
trial.
A High Court judge granted him leave to seek a judicial review of Mr Justice
Henry's refusal to give him a formal not-guilty verdict on the fraud and
false accounting charges he had faced, or to order that the Pounds 400,000
costs Lord Spens incurred before being granted legal aid should be paid out
of public funds. However, Mr Justice Macpherson said that, while he
recognised that Lord Spens felt a sense of injustice and had an arguable
case, 'I do not wish it to be thought that I believe there is much strength
in this case.'
The second Guinness trial was halted in February because of psychiatrists'
concern that Lord Spens' co-defendant, Mr Roger Seelig, a former corporate
finance director of the merchant bank Morgan Grenfell, could no longer
adequately defend himself.
Further prosecution of Mr Seelig was halted by a nolle prosequi, a decision
which stayed proceedings against him but was not an acquittal. The Serious
Fraud Office decided that in the circumstances, it would not be fair to
proceed further against Lord Spens.
In March Mr Justice Henry said that an order staying proceedings against
Lord Spens, with the charges left on the file, not to be proceeded with
without the court's permission, would put him in the same position as Mr
Seelig.
Refusing to grant Lord Spens a costs order, Mr Justice Henry said he had
brought the prosecution on himself by not consulting the Takeover Panel when
asked by Mr Seelig to recruit share supporters for Guinness under
indemnities against loss.
</TEXT>
