   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE increasingly bitter row over the future of Duckworth, the publisher,
moved to the High Court yesterday, Raymond Snoddy writes.
The Joseph Rowntree Reform Trust, a 26 per cent shareholder in Duckworth,
obtained injunctions against Mr Colin Haycraft, Duckworth chairman, and Mr
Stephen Hill of Lica Development Capital, an industrial development capital
group.
It is believed the injunctions prevent Mr Haycraft and Mr Hill talking to
potential investors or talking about the issues involved to the press.
In March, Mr Haycraft was sacked as chairman and chief executive of
Duckworth and locked out of the company's premises.
He returned last month after raising enough money to exercise an option that
took his shareholding in the company to 70 per cent.
In recent weeks Mr Haycraft has been trying to find new investors to secure
the future of the company.
