<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 92 / International Company News: Nicholas wins Dollars 15.8m
severance and stays on the payroll
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Nicholas Nicholas, the former co-chief executive of Time Warner whose
forced resignation was engineered in February by Mr Steve Ross, the
company's chairman, received a Dollars 15.8m severance payment in addition
to Dollars 2.9m of salary, deferred income and bonuses in 1991.
According to a new filing by Time Warner with the Securities &amp; Exchange
Commission (SEC), the company agreed not to cancel a 1989 employment
contract with Mr Nicholas. This will allow him to remain on the company's
payroll - at an annual salary of Dollars 250,000 - until 1999.
Mr Nicholas holds options to buy 500,000 shares in Time Warner at an average
of Dollars 90 per share. Yesterday's share price was Dollars 106 7/8 8, up
by  7/8 .
The size of executive compensation packages at Time Warner has been a
controversial issue for the company, mainly because Mr Ross is the recipient
of a Dollars 196m package related to payments for his stock interests in
Warner.
Last year Mr Ross received Dollars 4.06m in base pay, deferred income and a
bonus. In 1990 the total of Mr Ross's compensation - including a part of the
payment of Dollars 196m over eight years - was Dollars 78.2m.
Mr Jerry Levin, the former Time man who was elevated by Mr Ross to take the
place of Mr Nicholas as co-chief executive, was paid Dollars 2.8m in 1991.
</TEXT>
