<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 92 / Accounts rule change dropped
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A proposed requirement for companies to list their spending on items such as
advertising and training has been dropped from the forthcoming accounting
standard on the profit and loss account, it emerged yesterday.
The Accounting Standards Board said it would not include so-called revenue
investment activities in its second financial reporting standard, which is
due out in the autumn.
Revenue investment is designed to show expenditure charged to the profit and
loss account incurred to enhance profits. It includes spending on research
and development, and big maintenance and refurbishment projects.
The withdrawal comes after widespread condemnation of the proposal from
companies, which claimed that spending on these items was difficult to
identify, and that disclosure would threaten their competitive position.
But there was also a noticeable absence of support for the idea from users
of accounts during the consultation period on the standard, which closed in
March.
'We flew a kite but no one seemed to want revenue investment,' said Mr David
Tweedie, chairman of the board. 'It got a big raspberry. We don't feel this
is a big enough issue to make it worth retaining.'
In the exposure draft of the standard issued in December, revenue investment
was to be disclosed as a separate item in the profit and loss account.
The board has instead placed the onus on voluntary disclosure of revenue
investment by companies in its operational and financial review, details of
which were released in a discussion draft this week.
Most items which would have been required under the revenue investment
category are not currently disclosed. But companies already have to give
some details of research and development spending under the 1985 Companies
Act and Statement of Standard Accounting Practice 13.
The Institutional Investors' Committee, a body representing institutional
shareholders, earlier this week criticised the level of R&amp;D disclosure.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
