<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 92 / Observer: Redressed
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Problem. Minutes before the chairman of Britain's biggest bank addresses his
last annual general meeting, somebody pours white paint all over him. What
do you do?
How the officials of Barclays Bank answered the said challenge yesterday
would certainly win a distinction in any Institute of Bankers exam.
Loyal company servant John Moulding swiftly offered the chairman his own
suit, then shivered in his underpants while replacement pinstripes were
rushed in from Marks and Spencer. Meanwhile an apparently perfectly tailored
Sir John Quinton stepped on stage for his final bow.
What his thoughts were on the incident, nobody knows. But Barclays
non-executive director and ICI chairman Sir Denys Henderson reportedly
joked: 'I hope it was Dulux.'
