<PROFILE>_AN-CEAA3AGXFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920501
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 92 / Observer: Pilk's outsider
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
When a company has to look outside for a new chief executive, it is usually
an admission of failure. When the company in question is a world leader like
Pilkington, it is doubly so.
After more than 150 years in business, there is now only one Pilkington
among the famous glass-maker's leading lights. And while Sir Antony
Pilkington, the fifth generation of the family, is still chairman, he will
almost certainly be the last of the line. Like many dynasties Pilkington has
had trouble moving with the times and, despite boasting one of the
best-connected boards of non-executive directors, its management team has
long looked too inbred.
Roger Leverton, the new chief executive, is an international manager rather
than a glass man. Running RTZ's loss-making Indal business in North America,
he knows all about cyclical industries. He seems to made a success of
reshaping Indal's 28 subsidiaries and 8,000 staff in the depths of a
recession far worse than in the UK. He also has the benefit of a marketing
as distinct from a technical background.
That said, he still has to work under an executive chairman who has
dominated the company for more than a decade. Even though Leverton's title
is group chief executive, the City will need a lot of convincing that his
arrival at Pilkington means that there has been a significant change in the
power structure.
</TEXT>
