<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 92 / International Company News: UAL blames Dollars 92.3m loss on
weak domestic market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UAL, the parent company of United Airlines, yesterday revealed it lost
Dollars 92.3m after tax in the first three months of 1992. Mr Stephen Wolf,
chairman, described the result 'woefully unsatisfactory'.
The net loss compared with an after-tax deficit of Dollars 157m in the same
period a year ago. However, this was when the Gulf war lead to a sharp
decline in traffic levels.
United is one of three US 'mega-carriers', and its first-quarter deficit
follows a modest Dollars 20m profit from American Airlines and a Dollars
151.6m deficit at Delta Air Lines, its two big rivals.
At the operating level, UAL saw even larger losses, totalling Dollars 146.3m
in the first three months of 1992, compared with a Dollars 268.1m deficit a
year ago. Operating revenues were up from Dollars 2.56bn to Dollars 2.97bn,
but costs rose from Dollars 2.83bn to Dollars 3.12bn, despite a reduction in
fuel expenses to Dollars 363.4m from Dollars 448.1m.
United, which recently acquired the former Pan Am routes in Latin America,
blamed the results on the domestic market.
'The anaemic economic recovery in the US, where United has about two-thirds
of its capacity, coupled with the pricing actions of certain carriers, had a
very significant impact on first-quarter revenue,' said Mr Wolf.
Some analysts have been sceptical about the speed and ease with which the
Pan Am business could be integrated.
However, Mr Wolf stressed the airline's primary focus was 'on further
development' of the international route system. Here, he said, first-quarter
capacity was up by 39 per cent, and traffic by 55 per cent.
United's yield - passenger revenue per mile flown - rose by 2.8 per cent, to
13.60 cents, while its load factor was 61 per cent, up 2.1 percentage points
from the 58.9 per cent seen a year ago. Its shares were up by Dollars  3/4 ,
at Dollars 124 3/4 . Amid a series of management appointments, United
Airlines yesterday named Mr John Pope, formerly vice-chairman and chief
financial officer, to be the carrier's chief operating officer. Mr Pope
becomes responsible for day-to-day matters such as operations, marketing,
planning and customer service.
Mr Stephen Wolf, who remains chairman and chief executive, will concentrate
on strategy, and government and market relationships. The company is also
establishing an international division, which will be headed by Mr James
Goodwin, previously senior vice-president for maintainance operations.
