<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 92 / International Company News: US broker defends bond trades
with insurer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Agencies
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MERRILL LYNCH yesterday told a Senate subcommittee its junk bond trades with
Guarantee Security Life Insurance, the insolvent Florida insurer, were
proper, and did not constitute illegal 'parking' of securities, Agencies
report. The broker, the biggest in the US, is defending itself before the
permanent investigations subcommittee, chaired by the powerful Democrat, Nr
Sam Nunn.
Merrill executives said its dealings with the insurer were reported to the
state insurance regulators in Florida. Parking refers to a short-term sale
and repurchase of securities, with the aim of dressing-up an investment
portfolio temporarily.
However, Mr Nunn reportedly peppered Merrill Lynch witnesses with pointed
questions suggesting the trades were not real transactions. The Florida
insurance commissioner, Mr Tom Gallagher, has already told the subcommittee
the trades were merely paper transactions used by the insurer to inflate its
assets.
Guarantee Security was seized by the regulators in August and declared
insolvent. Since then, the deputy receiver for the insurer has alleged that
Merrill helped to hide Guarantee's holdings of high-yield securities from
regulators, by temporarily exchanging them for government securities at the
end of each financial year.
Merrill has denied any impropriety, but the insurance regulators have filed
a civil suit against the brokerage house, along with certain former advisers
to the company.
The Senate hearings come at a time when insurance in the US has acquired
heavy political overtones, adds Nikki Tait in New York. Some members of the
Democrat-controlled Congress are attempting to introduce some form of
federal supervision of the sector.
</TEXT>
