<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 92 / International Company News: PWA deficit climbs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LOSSES at PWA, the holding company of Canadian Airlines International,
climbed 17 per cent in the first quarter, despite a 3 per cent rise in
revenues and improved load factors.
The Calgary-based company, which is trying to ensure its survival by
negotiating a partnership with the US carrier, American Airlines,
acknowledged that a return to profitability was unlikely this year.
Canadian's main rival, Air Canada, which is also in the red, said it was
cutting another 350 jobs as part of an effort to return to an operating
profit within the next 12 months. The job losses include 10 per cent of the
airline's management positions.
PWA suffered a first-quarter loss of CDollars 74.9m (USDollars 62m), or
CDollars 1.56 a share, up from CDollars 63.8m, or CDollars 1.70, a year
earlier. The lower per-share loss is due to a larger number of outstanding
shares.
The airline ascribed the higher loss to fierce fare-discounting, despite a
rise in its passenger load factor to 64.8 per cent from 59.5 per cent. Air
Canada suffered a CDollars 218m loss last year, but said it aimed for a
CDollars 300m turnround by the end of 1993.
</TEXT>
