</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THOMSON, the French state-owned electronics group which is negotiating to
merge some of its interests with CEA-Industrie, the nuclear energy group,
cut its net losses in 1991 to FFr702m (Dollars 125.8m) from FFr2.47bn in
1990.
The group, which is the linchpin of France's public sector with extensive
interests across the electronics industry, produced a profit in its defence
electronics subsidiary, but lost money in its consumer electronics
interests, which were hit by a restructuring charge of FFr1.5bn. It
succeeded in turning its consolidated loss of FFr1.6bn in 1990 into profits
(before payments to minorities) of FFr227m.
Thomson-CSF, the defence electronics division, saw its net profits rise from
FFr2.17bn to FFr2.35bn on sales which slipped by 5 per cent to FFr35.18bn.
The fall in sales was largely due to a reduced contribution from its Al
Thakeb contract in the Middle East.
The consumer electronics division, Thomson-CE, remained in the red with a
net loss of FFr2.48bn on sales which fell by 6 per cent to FFr31.16bn.
Thomson Electromenager saw its sales rise by 2 per cent to FFr5.08bn,
contributing to group consolidated sales of FFr71.28bn, which fell by 5 per
cent during the year.
