FT  01 MAY 92 / International Company News: Hafnia board withdraws support
for Skandia bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By XUELING LIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   COPENHAGEN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE month-long struggle by Skandia, the Swedish insurance group, to take
over Denmark's second largest insurer, Hafnia, ended yesterday after
Hafnia's board of directors said it would now support the rescue package
proposed by the group of Danish shareholders dissatisfied with the Swedish
offer. Previously the board had given its full support to the Skandia bid.
The reversal of Hafnia's original agreement with Skandia took place after
the deadline for a final statement from Skandia's board was postponed. The
Skandia statement was expected following a 'due diligence report' carried
out on Hafnia.
Mr Ebbe Christensen, chairman of Hafnia's board, said that he could
'understand if Skandia were disappointed because they no longer had an
agreement where they thought they had one'.
But Mr Christensen said that he hoped it would still be possible to
establish a future co-operation with the Skandia.
The agreement between Hafnia's board and the group of Danish shareholders
involves a DKr1.5bn (Dollars 234.3m) increase in Hafnia's share capital
through a rights issue.
The two institutional shareholders, the LD Fund and the Local Authorities
Pension Insurance Fund, which have led the disaffected Danish shareholders,
have welcomed the move.
