FT  01 MAY 92 / UK Company News: McLaughlin &amp; Harvey Pounds 5.4m loss
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
IN THE most difficult year in its history, McLaughlin &amp; Harvey, the
construction group, incurred a pre-tax loss of Pounds 5.4m and passed its
dividend.
This followed losses of Pounds 4.9m at the half-way stage, when provisions
of Pounds 4.05m were made for bad debts and write-down for construction work
in progress.
The company said that conditions in the industry had worsened in the second
half, but although further provisions had been made they were on a much
reduced scale.
Mr Charles Denny, chairman, said that the Northern Ireland division had
secured a substantial workload this year. However, turnover in south-east
England was expected to be diminished as the company was not prepared to
accept work at negative margins.
Sales fell to Pounds 98.4m, against Pounds 110m in 1990 when there was a
pre-tax loss of Pounds 727,000. Losses per share jumped from 11.6p to 80.3p.
